# Python Backend Rules

## Route Files (`api/routes/`)
- One router file per domain (accounts, budget, chat, etc.)
- Pydantic request/response models defined INLINE in the route file
- All routes use `session: AsyncSession = Depends(get_session)` for DB access
- Return proper HTTP status codes (201 for creates, 404 for not found, etc.)
- Validate inputs with Pydantic — never trust raw request data

## Pipeline Modules (`pipeline/`)
- Business logic lives in `pipeline/`, NOT in route files
- Routes are thin orchestrators: validate → call pipeline → return response
- AI calls go through `pipeline/ai/` (categorizer, chat, report_gen, tax_analyzer)
- Import logic lives in `pipeline/importers/`
- Planning engines live in `pipeline/planning/`

## Database Access
- ORM models: `pipeline/db/schema.py` (single source of truth)
- DAL functions: `pipeline/db/models.py`
- Use `AsyncSession` with `select()`, `insert()`, `update()` — avoid raw SQL except in migrations
- Always handle `IntegrityError` for unique constraints
- Commit happens in `get_session()` context manager — don't call `session.commit()` manually in routes

## Error Handling
- Raise `HTTPException` with descriptive messages in routes
- Use `logger.error()` for unexpected failures (never log PII)
- Catch specific exceptions, not bare `except:`

## File Size
- Route files: target <400 lines; split into sub-routers if exceeding 500
- Pipeline modules: target <300 lines; extract helpers into focused files
- Schema: `schema.py` is intentionally large (single source of truth) — this is acceptable
